---
import CourseLayout from '../../layouts/CourseLayout.astro';

const sections = [
  { id: 'embeddings', label: 'Word Embeddings' },
  { id: 'tokenization', label: 'Tokenization' },
  { id: 'language-modeling', label: 'Language Modeling' },
  { id: 'transformers', label: 'The Transformer' },
  { id: 'scaling', label: 'Scaling Laws' },
];

/* Math-heavy strings defined here so that LaTeX braces don't clash with JSX. */
const math = {
  embeddingDef: String.raw`A learned mapping $f: \mathcal{V} \to \mathbb{R}^d$ from a vocabulary $\mathcal{V}$ to a $d$-dimensional real vector space, where semantic and syntactic relationships between words are encoded as geometric relationships between their vectors.`,
  analogy: String.raw`$$\vec{v}_{\text{king}} - \vec{v}_{\text{man}} + \vec{v}_{\text{woman}} \approx \vec{v}_{\text{queen}}$$`,
  chainRule: String.raw`$$P(x_1, x_2, \ldots, x_T) = \prod_{t=1}^{T} P(x_t \mid x_1, \ldots, x_{t-1})$$`,
  attentionDef: String.raw`A mechanism where each position in a sequence computes a weighted sum over all positions, with weights determined by learned compatibility functions. Given queries $Q$, keys $K$, and values $V$:`,
  attention: String.raw`$$\text{Attention}(Q, K, V) = \text{softmax}\!\left(\frac{QK^T}{\sqrt{d_k}}\right)V$$`,
  scalingLaw: String.raw`$$L(N) \propto N^{-\alpha}$$`,
  scalingCaption: String.raw`Loss scales as a power law with model parameters $N$, where $\alpha \approx 0.076$ for Transformers.`,
};
---

<CourseLayout
  day={1}
  title="Foundations"
  description="From Embeddings to Transformers — how machines represent meaning as geometry, and how the architecture that changed everything actually works."
  sections={sections}
>

  <!-- ===== WORD EMBEDDINGS ===== -->
  <section id="embeddings">
    <h2>Word Embeddings</h2>
    <p>
      Before a language model can do anything useful, it needs a way to
      represent words as numbers. Not just any numbers&mdash;numbers that
      capture <em>meaning</em>. Word embeddings are the solution: they map each
      word to a point in a high-dimensional vector space, arranged so that words
      with similar meanings sit near each other.
    </p>

    <div class="definition-box">
      <p class="definition-box__label">Definition</p>
      <p class="definition-box__term">Word Embedding</p>
      <p set:html={math.embeddingDef} />
    </div>

    <p>
      The key insight behind Word2Vec (Mikolov et al., 2013) is
      deceptively simple: words that appear in similar contexts tend to have
      similar meanings. Instead of hand-crafting features, we learn embeddings
      by training a shallow neural network to predict context words from a
      target word (Skip-gram) or a target word from its context (CBOW).
    </p>

    <div class="formula-block">
      <p set:html={math.analogy} />
      <p class="formula-block__caption">The classic analogy: vector arithmetic captures semantic relationships.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="stop-and-think">
      <div class="stop-and-think__header">
        <svg class="stop-and-think__icon" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round">
          <circle cx="12" cy="12" r="10"/>
          <path d="M9.09 9a3 3 0 0 1 5.83 1c0 2-3 3-3 3"/>
          <line x1="12" y1="17" x2="12.01" y2="17"/>
        </svg>
        <span class="stop-and-think__label">Stop and Think</span>
      </div>
      <p>
        If word embeddings place semantically similar words near each other,
        what happens to words with multiple meanings&mdash;like "bank" (river
        bank vs. financial bank)? What limitation does this reveal about static
        embeddings?
      </p>
      <details>
        <summary>Reveal</summary>
        <div>
          <p>
            Static embeddings assign a <strong>single vector</strong> per word,
            regardless of context. "Bank" gets one representation that averages
            across all its senses. This is a fundamental limitation that
            contextual embeddings (like those produced by Transformers) address
            by generating different representations for the same word depending
            on surrounding context.
          </p>
        </div>
      </details>
    </div>

    <div class="course-note">
      <svg class="course-note__icon" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round">
        <path d="M14 2H6a2 2 0 0 0-2 2v16a2 2 0 0 0 2 2h12a2 2 0 0 0 2-2V8z"/>
        <polyline points="14 2 14 8 20 8"/>
        <line x1="16" y1="13" x2="8" y2="13"/>
        <line x1="16" y1="17" x2="8" y2="17"/>
      </svg>
      <p>
        <strong>Social science connection:</strong> Caliskan et al. (2017) showed
        that word embeddings trained on large corpora absorb societal biases&mdash;a
        finding with profound implications for using these representations in
        research.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ===== TOKENIZATION ===== -->
  <section id="tokenization">
    <h2>Tokenization</h2>
    <p>
      Before text enters a model, it must be split into discrete units the model
      can process. Tokenization bridges raw text and the embedding layer, and
      the choice of tokenization strategy has real consequences for model
      behavior.
    </p>

    <div class="definition-box">
      <p class="definition-box__label">Definition</p>
      <p class="definition-box__term">Subword Tokenization</p>
      <p>
        A tokenization strategy that splits text into units smaller than words
        but larger than characters. Common algorithms include Byte-Pair Encoding
        (BPE) and WordPiece. This balances vocabulary size against the ability
        to represent any input text, including rare or unseen words.
      </p>
    </div>

    <p>
      Modern LLMs use subword tokenizers that learn a vocabulary from data.
      BPE starts with individual characters and iteratively merges the most
      frequent pairs. The result is a vocabulary where common words are single
      tokens, while rare words are composed of multiple subword pieces.
    </p>

    <div class="key-takeaway">
      <p class="key-takeaway__label">Key Takeaway</p>
      <p>
        Tokenization is not just preprocessing&mdash;it fundamentally shapes
        what a model "sees." Multilingual tokenizers often allocate fewer tokens
        to non-English text, meaning the model has lower effective resolution for
        those languages. When working with multilingual social science data, always
        check how your text tokenizes.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ===== LANGUAGE MODELING ===== -->
  <section id="language-modeling">
    <h2>Language Modeling</h2>
    <p>
      At its core, a language model learns a probability distribution over
      sequences of tokens. The dominant paradigm for modern LLMs is
      <strong>autoregressive language modeling</strong>: predict the next token
      given all previous tokens.
    </p>

    <div class="formula-block">
      <p set:html={math.chainRule} />
      <p class="formula-block__caption">The chain rule decomposition underlying autoregressive language models.</p>
    </div>

    <p>
      This framing is powerful because it turns language understanding into a
      prediction problem that can be trained on vast amounts of unlabeled text.
      The model's "understanding" of language emerges from learning to predict
      what comes next&mdash;a task that requires implicit knowledge of syntax,
      semantics, and even world knowledge.
    </p>

    <div class="stop-and-think">
      <div class="stop-and-think__header">
        <svg class="stop-and-think__icon" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round">
          <circle cx="12" cy="12" r="10"/>
          <path d="M9.09 9a3 3 0 0 1 5.83 1c0 2-3 3-3 3"/>
          <line x1="12" y1="17" x2="12.01" y2="17"/>
        </svg>
        <span class="stop-and-think__label">Stop and Think</span>
      </div>
      <p>
        A model trained only to predict the next word can summarize documents,
        answer questions, translate between languages, and write code. Why would
        next-token prediction produce such general capabilities?
      </p>
      <details>
        <summary>Reveal</summary>
        <div>
          <p>
            To predict the next token accurately across diverse text, the model
            must build internal representations of syntax, semantics, factual
            knowledge, reasoning patterns, and more. The prediction objective is
            simple, but <em>solving it well</em> on internet-scale data requires
            sophisticated internal representations that transfer to downstream
            tasks.
          </p>
        </div>
      </details>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ===== THE TRANSFORMER ===== -->
  <section id="transformers">
    <h2>The Transformer</h2>
    <p>
      The Transformer architecture (Vaswani et al., 2017) is the engine behind
      every modern LLM. Its key innovation is <strong>self-attention</strong>:
      a mechanism that lets each token attend to every other token in the
      sequence, learning which parts of the context matter most for each
      prediction.
    </p>

    <div class="definition-box">
      <p class="definition-box__label">Definition</p>
      <p class="definition-box__term">Self-Attention</p>
      <p set:html={math.attentionDef} />
    </div>

    <div class="formula-block">
      <p set:html={math.attention} />
      <p class="formula-block__caption">Scaled dot-product attention &mdash; the core operation of the Transformer.</p>
    </div>

    <p>
      Unlike recurrent networks that process tokens sequentially, the
      Transformer processes all positions in parallel, using positional
      encodings to retain order information. This parallelism is what makes
      Transformers trainable on massive datasets with modern hardware.
    </p>

    <div class="key-takeaway">
      <p class="key-takeaway__label">Key Takeaway</p>
      <p>
        The Transformer replaced recurrence with attention, trading sequential
        computation for parallelism. This architectural choice is why LLMs could
        scale to billions of parameters trained on trillions of tokens&mdash;the
        foundation of their remarkable capabilities.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ===== SCALING LAWS ===== -->
  <section id="scaling">
    <h2>Scaling Laws</h2>
    <p>
      One of the most consequential discoveries in modern AI is that language
      model performance improves <em>predictably</em> as you increase model
      size, dataset size, and compute. These relationships, known as scaling
      laws (Kaplan et al., 2020), follow power-law curves.
    </p>

    <div class="formula-block">
      <p set:html={math.scalingLaw} />
      <p class="formula-block__caption" set:html={math.scalingCaption} />
    </div>

    <p>
      Scaling laws mean that, within broad regimes, we can predict how much
      better a model will be before training it&mdash;a remarkable property that
      has guided the development of GPT-3, GPT-4, Claude, and their successors.
    </p>

    <div class="key-takeaway">
      <p class="key-takeaway__label">Key Takeaway</p>
      <p>
        Scaling laws are why the field has converged on "bigger is better" for
        pretraining. But they also raise important questions: how far can
        scaling go, and what capabilities emerge only at scale? For social
        scientists, understanding scaling helps explain why larger models
        perform qualitatively differently on complex tasks.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="course-note">
      <svg class="course-note__icon" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round">
        <path d="M2 3h6a4 4 0 0 1 4 4v14a3 3 0 0 0-3-3H2z"/>
        <path d="M22 3h-6a4 4 0 0 0-4 4v14a3 3 0 0 1 3-3h7z"/>
      </svg>
      <p>
        <strong>Reading:</strong> Kaplan et al. (2020), "Scaling Laws for Neural
        Language Models" &mdash; the paper that quantified these relationships and
        shaped the trajectory of the entire field.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

</CourseLayout>
